description:
Re-filed from holomush-zcgw.6 (2026-05-16 epic audit of holomush-zcgw).

Location: web/src/lib/components/terminal/AnsiRenderer.svelte

  const ansiUp = new AnsiUp();
  ansiUp.use_classes = false;
  let html = $derived(ansiUp.ansi_to_html(text));
  // ...
  <span class="ansi-output">{@html html}</span>

ansi_up v6 does HTML-escape non-ANSI characters before producing its output, which makes it safe against XSS for typical text. However, this safety property is not enforced by the code — it is implicit. The risk here is:

1. A future upgrade of ansi_up could change this behavior without an explicit test.
2. The code also lacks a test asserting that HTML special characters in text are escaped in the output.
3. use_classes = false is set, which produces inline style attributes. While not exploitable on its own, it means the output is more complex HTML that is harder to audit.

Additionally, EventRenderer.svelte falls through to AnsiRenderer only when hasAnsiCodes(event.text) is true, but the 'generic' branch at the bottom calls linkUrls(@html) unconditionally without going through AnsiRenderer — so the critical XSS in linkUrls is the primary concern.

Recommendation: Add a unit test asserting that ansi_up escapes HTML in input (e.g., '<script>' becomes '&lt;script&gt;'). Explicitly document the security invariant in a comment. Consider calling DOMPurify as a defense-in-depth wrapper even if ansi_up is expected to escape.

## Location

web/src/lib/comm/CommunicationLine.svelte — the channel-prefix conditional inside say (line 22) and pose (line 24):

```svelte
{:else if line.kind === 'say'}
  {#if line.channel}<span class="channel-prefix">[{line.channel}]</span>{' '}{/if}<span class="speaker">...
{:else if line.kind === 'pose'}
  {#if line.channel}<span class="channel-prefix">[{line.channel}]</span>{' '}{/if}<span class="actor">...
```

## What's wrong

No test in the PR passes a `CommLine` with `channel` set. The `commLine.test.ts` adapter tests assert `channel: undefined` in every output, and the rendering tests never supply a channel value. The `channel-prefix` CSS class is never exercised.

This is a pre-existing gap (the old CommunicationRenderer had identical branches and was also untested), but this PR introduces `CommunicationLine.svelte` as a new file and the gap is in scope.

## Why it matters

Channel-prefixed communication is a game feature (OOC channels, faction channels, etc.). A regression that dropped the `[ChannelName]` prefix would be invisible to CI.

## Suggested fix

Add one test to `CommunicationLine.svelte.test.ts` (or `commLine.test.ts` for the adapter):

```ts
it('renders a say with channel prefix before the speaker', () => {
  const { text } = render({ kind: 'say', actor: 'Bob', text: 'Ready.', channel: 'Ops' });
  expect(text).toBe('[Ops] Bob says, "Ready."');
});
```

## Location

web/src/lib/components/scenes/PoseCard.svelte (the if/else contentWarning block introduced in this PR):

```svelte
{#if entry.contentWarning}
  <details>
    <summary class="cw">CW: {entry.contentWarning}</summary>
    <CommunicationLine {line} />
  </details>
{:else}
  <CommunicationLine {line} />
{/if}
```

## What's wrong

All 5 tests in `PoseCard.svelte.test.ts` pass entries without `contentWarning`. The content-warning `<details>`/`<summary>` branch is never mounted. A regression that, say, swapped the if/else arms (rendering the CW summary unconditionally while hiding the normal flow) would pass the full test suite.

## Why it matters

Content warnings are a player-safety feature. An untested branch here is low severity in practice (the branch is simple), but the PR explicitly refactored PoseCard and added tests — a CW entry is straightforward to add.

## Suggested fix

Add one test to `PoseCard.svelte.test.ts`:

```ts
it('wraps a content-warned entry in a disclosure widget showing the CW label', () => {
  const { html, text } = render(entry({ contentWarning: 'violence', text: 'He draws.' }));
  expect(html).toContain('<details');
  expect(text).toContain('CW: violence');
});
```

internal/plugin/pluginauthz/evaluate.go:253-255:

  // splitResourceRef parses "type:id" and requires both halves non-empty.
  // Per spec §3 the resource format is exactly "type:id" (single colon); a
  // resource whose id half still contains a colon is rejected (ok=false).

The comment says the spec format is 'exactly type:id (single colon)'. The implementation uses strings.IndexByte (takes the FIRST colon), then checks if the id half contains another colon and rejects it. So 'a:b:c' is rejected, not silently accepted.

The comment is not wrong about the rejection, but it could mislead a reader about WHY: the current implementation uses first-colon parsing, not a strict single-colon parser. If someone replaces strings.IndexByte with strings.Count(ref, ':') == 1 (a strict single-colon approach), behavior would differ for strings like 'a:b:c' (currently rejected via the contains-colon guard; with strict approach, also rejected — same outcome but different code path).

More importantly, the comment elides a subtle implementation detail the ABAC reviewer flagged: for inputs like 'a:b:c', the current code takes type='a', id='b:c', then rejects because 'b:c' contains a colon. This is correct but is not the 'single colon' parse the comment implies — it's first-colon + post-check. A future editor who reads the comment and 'optimizes' to a direct single-colon check would get the same result in this case, but if the colon-in-id check is ever relaxed or the comment is used to justify treating id as everything after the first colon without the guard, the spec violation would be silent.

Fix: Clarify the comment to state the actual implementation: 'splitResourceRef splits on the first colon; the id half MUST NOT contain a further colon — inputs of the form type:subtype:id are rejected.'

This is a suggestion-level comment accuracy issue; the rejection behavior is correctly documented, only the mechanism description is imprecise.

plugins/core-scenes/commands.go:268-269 (context lines touched by this PR via the nolint removal at 267-268):

  // handleResume transitions a paused scene back to active. Owner-only in
  // Phase 2; Phase 3 widens to any member per spec D6.

The comment frames this as a future-state description ('Phase 3 widens'), but the active policy in plugins/core-scenes/plugin.yaml:138-141 already reads:

  - name: resume-scene-as-participant
    dsl: >-
      permit(principal is character, action in ["resume"], resource is scene) when { principal.id in resource.scene.participants
      };

The 'Phase 3 widens to any member' state is already shipped. The comment describes a past planning state rather than current behavior. A developer reading it would believe resume is currently owner-only (Phase 2) and that the widening is still pending.

Note: this comment was not added by the PR but is in lines that the PR's diff context touches (the nolint removal immediately above). It falls within scope because the PR author touched this region and the existing comment is now inaccurate relative to the code shipped in this same PR (the gated dispatch at commands.go:73 passes action 'resume' to the engine, which checks the participant policy, not an owner policy).

Fix: Update the comment to: 'handleResume transitions a paused scene back to active. Any scene participant may resume (enforced by the resume-scene-as-participant ABAC policy).'

Deferred suggestion from PR #4312 review (was holomush-n0e3x.2).

Pattern P-3 (over-explanation). plugins/core-scenes/store_integration_test.go around the ReadSceneLogForSnapshot insertLog helper. The current 38-word comment re-explains the mechanism and hedges with 'without depending on ulid.Make()'s wall-clock + global monotonic entropy source', which names the replaced mechanism rather than describing the code.

Suggested fix: trim to the invariant, e.g.:
  // Make ids strictly increasing by construction: sequential time
  // component, zero entropy — guarantees ORDER BY id ASC == insert order.

